You don&#39;t want to register model twice - in `OrderAdmin` and also in parent class. This can produce some weird effects (like with actions, in your case). Clean way to re-use functionality across ModelAdmin classes is to put it to mixin and then include that mixin wherever needed. Like this:
```
class CommonAdminMixin:
    actions = [&#39;some_action&#39;]


@admin.register(Order)
class OrderAdmin(CommonAdminMixin, models.Admin):
    actions = []


@admin.register(AnotherModel)
class AnotherAdmin(CommonAdminMixin, models.Admin):
    ...
```

Similar to the mixin solution, but I would use a parent class instead which will allow you to call `super()` within the methods without any weirdness.

```python
class BaseAdmin(admin.ModelAdmin):
    actions = [&#39;some_action&#39;]


@admin.register(Order)
class OrderAdmin(BaseAdmin):
    model = Order


@admin.register(AnotherModel)
class AnotherAdmin(BaseAdmin):
    model = AnotherModel
    actions = []
```

You just override `admin.ModelAdmin` in the `BaseAdmin` class and inherit from `BaseAdmin` instead. You can then effectively treat `BaseAdmin` like `admin.ModelAdmin`

